ebate - from relations between Western and Islamic cultures, to the political significance of the private conscience in a liberal society - are anticipated in the romantic era.Key FeaturesExplains the historical, political and aesthetic significance of Scott's 'Tory scepticism'Considers the relationship between Scott's interests and twentieth-first-century debates about nation, empire, community, identity and state legitimacyIncludes detailed analyses of three of Scott's most influential poemsOffers detailed, and carefully historicised interpretations in an accessible style  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aLiterature and societyxHistoryx19th centuryxScotland. 0aLiterature and societyxHistoryy19th centuryxScotland. 0aLiterature and societyzScotlandxHistoryy19th century. 4aLiterary Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEdinburgh University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2013-2000z97831107804680 cprintz978074862606940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780748631353?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780748631353423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780748631353/original  a978-3-11-078046-8  Edinburgh University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2013-2000c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK